üìå Understanding the Service Layer in Spring Boot JDBC
The Service Layer in a Spring Boot application acts as a business logic layer, 
that processes data before passing it to the Controller Layer or receiving data from the Repository Layer.

üîπ What Does the Service Layer Do?
1Ô∏è‚É£ Acts as a middle layer between the Controller and Repository.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Contains business logic (e.g., validation, calculations, transformations).
3Ô∏è‚É£ Calls repository methods to interact with the database.
4Ô∏è‚É£ Provides a clean separation between database access and application logic.


Implementation:
package com.example.demo.service;

import com.example.demo.model.Employee;
import com.example.demo.repository.EmployeeRepository;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;
import java.util.List;

@Service
public class EmployeeService {

    @Autowired
    private EmployeeRepository repository;

    public int addEmployee(Employee employee) {
        return repository.save(employee);
    }

    public List<Employee> getAllEmployees() {
        return repository.findAll();
    }

    public Employee getEmployeeById(int id) {
        return repository.findById(id);
    }

    public int removeEmployee(int id) {
        return repository.deleteById(id);
    }
}
